WEBVTT

00:08.900 --> 00:12.900
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

00:30.000 --> 00:34.980
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

00:37.760 --> 00:39.360
And here are your hosts.

00:44.780 --> 00:47.460
This is Bill Vernon and David Cruz.

00:47.860 --> 00:52.100
Philip Jose Farmer has been a mainstay science fiction writer since 1952.

00:52.700 --> 00:57.520
He has written over 40 novels and over 80 short stories focusing on a wide variety of subjects.

00:58.060 --> 01:03.680
These range from Tarzan to the afterlife, from sex-crazed aliens to a star-faring Catholic

01:03.680 --> 01:08.680
priest. Farmer's most famous works are the River World series, The World of Tears series,

01:09.060 --> 01:14.500
his erotic fantasy novels, and the story later a novel The Lovers. We ask Farmer how he started

01:14.500 --> 01:20.140
writing science fiction. I started reading science fiction when I was seven years old.

01:20.140 --> 01:26.760
I'm 63 now, and I knew I always wanted to be a writer.

01:27.540 --> 01:34.860
All I did was do much about it for many years. The funny thing is I actually intended to become

01:34.860 --> 01:42.200
a mainstream writer, that is to write stories which are not in particular genre. But I somehow

01:42.200 --> 01:48.800
just drifted into science fiction and sold my first science fiction story in 1952.

01:49.940 --> 01:57.860
That was called The Lovers. It was a novel novel that was published in a magazine, and it's generally

01:57.860 --> 02:04.640
credited with breaking the taboo against the mature use of sex in science fiction magazines.

02:05.940 --> 02:10.340
We asked Farmer if he consciously set out to break taboos by writing The Lovers.

02:11.740 --> 02:17.900
No, I had an idea for a story, and I couldn't write it unless I broke the taboo. I didn't

02:17.900 --> 02:24.320
really consciously set out to do it because I had the idea, and I thought it was terrific.

02:24.620 --> 02:28.660
On the other hand, I knew I was going to have a lot of trouble getting an accepted idea.

02:29.140 --> 02:37.400
I did have a lot of trouble. The first editor I sent it to, John Campbell, the editor of The

02:39.500 --> 02:43.980
Lovers, was the most prestigious and highest paying market, and actually I sent it to him first.

02:45.160 --> 02:47.800
He returned it with a comment that I'm not sure you're reading.

02:49.600 --> 02:56.160
So I sent it to Horace Gold, who was editing Galaxy, which was equally prestigious and had

02:56.680 --> 03:04.380
about the same word rate. His comments were something like John Campbell's. Then I sent it to

03:05.040 --> 03:09.720
Samuel Mines, who was editor of a magazine called Starling Stories.

03:12.500 --> 03:18.880
He immediately accepted it and knew it was a revolutionary breakthrough. He published it,

03:18.980 --> 03:26.980
and I was on my way. Accepted the next story I wrote was also equally revolutionary, and

03:27.640 --> 03:31.540
it took me a year before I could get anybody to accept it.

03:33.820 --> 03:38.360
Farmer is also interested in religion and its varied forms, and has used it in his works.

03:39.520 --> 03:46.360
My interest in religion has manifested itself throughout all my work. Although a lot of people,

03:46.560 --> 03:52.720
when they say the name Farmer, immediately think of sex in both. Fact is I've written much more

03:52.720 --> 04:01.080
about religion than about sex, or sometimes both at the same time. In some respects,

04:02.620 --> 04:10.160
sex and religion are two sides of the same coin. In certain fields of activity.

04:15.700 --> 04:21.060
But religion is only one of many themes. Farmer feels that he may have labored in relative anonymity

04:21.060 --> 04:24.700
for years because his writings are so varied, but he has his reasons.

04:25.520 --> 04:32.740
One of the reasons I've had trouble in the early days, I think really becoming identified and

04:32.740 --> 04:40.720
getting a ban of followers is that I didn't beat on just one or two drums. I ranged all over the

04:40.720 --> 04:50.340
field. But I find out that if I do a variety of stuff and I don't get tired, each new novel

04:50.860 --> 04:53.420
challenge, I'm not just working the same old theme again.

04:54.400 --> 04:57.560
Tomorrow we continue with more on Philip Jose Farmer.

05:05.020 --> 05:09.820
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction

05:09.820 --> 05:13.680
Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

05:20.340 --> 05:50.180
Thank you.

