Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

06:16.800 --> 06:22.140
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

06:24.840 --> 06:26.500
And here are your hosts.

06:31.700 --> 06:36.520
This is Bill Vernon and David Cruz. We're continuing our interview with Philip Jose Farmer.

06:36.980 --> 06:41.300
We want to explore here some background related to one of Farmer's major themes, religion.

06:42.080 --> 06:46.700
As Farmer allowed earlier, he considers himself a writer of religious themes even more so than a

06:46.700 --> 06:50.400
writer of sexual themes. His own religious background is quite checkered.

07:02.320 --> 07:08.540
And I always wrestled all my life with the problems of immortality,

07:09.100 --> 07:15.420
pre-bestion, grace, the afterlife, and all that sort of stuff. I was raised as a

07:17.040 --> 07:25.940
Christian scientist up until the time I was about 12, and then I was sent to a Presbyterian church

07:28.620 --> 07:35.300
where there was a conflict between Christian science and the Presbyterian idea of predestination.

07:36.880 --> 07:41.880
And then when I was about 16, I guess I became an atheist. Now I've gone through

07:43.900 --> 07:48.920
atheism, through agnosticism, and then I was converted to the disciples of Christ.

07:50.060 --> 07:57.140
And then I backslid, fell from grace, and as the theological term goes,

07:58.220 --> 08:03.480
and then I lapsed back into agnosticism. And what are Farmer's present beliefs?

08:04.700 --> 08:12.820
My present situation is that without immortality, life has no meaning. If there's a creation,

08:12.820 --> 08:21.020
there must be a creator. But I've become tremendously interested in what to sometimes

08:21.020 --> 08:31.280
refer to as mythism. It isn't really like the Muslims, the Muslims' Sufism school. Then

08:32.540 --> 08:40.320
a lot of related stuff like that. You might see right now, I'm in a sort of a limbo,

08:41.280 --> 08:46.460
heading towards something I don't know what. The concept of an afterlife appears repeatedly in

08:46.460 --> 08:52.180
Farmer's works. Well, if you think about it, there could be a million different possibilities

08:52.180 --> 09:02.300
in an afterlife of their work. But one of my perhaps unstated themes is that immortality

09:03.120 --> 09:10.300
may not depend upon a supernatural being that's in the evolutionary drives of man,

09:10.320 --> 09:19.820
for him to invent immortality himself. Drawback to that is, those people who are already dead

09:19.820 --> 09:26.220
will remain dead, right? So that doesn't correspond to the religious idea of immortality,

09:26.300 --> 09:32.580
where everybody is raised from the first human being to the last one.

09:34.040 --> 09:40.780
I like to do a lot of variations on that. I have a new book called The Unreasoning Mask.

09:41.160 --> 09:47.960
That's the quotation we'll be dick. And this is concerned with theology,

09:48.680 --> 09:56.340
of afterlife, immortality. You might call it a philosophical theological space offer.

10:12.820 --> 10:13.380
So,

10:13.380 --> 10:18.480
many of Farmer's first works had the central theme of religion. The lovers and a woman a day

10:18.480 --> 10:23.540
deal with a future amalgamation of church and state called the Sturge. A popular character,

10:23.540 --> 10:28.580
Father John Carmody, is a planet hopping Catholic priest who has appeared in several short stories.

10:29.140 --> 10:33.260
We learn about his former life and conversion in the excellent novel Night of Light.

10:34.180 --> 10:39.040
Inside, Outside is a wild tale about the afterlife and immortality. It is in fact the

10:39.040 --> 10:43.340
predecessor to the famous Riverworld series, which we will discuss in our next show.

10:49.980 --> 10:55.360
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, a production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction

10:55.360 --> 10:59.220
Association produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

11:44.460 --> 11:48.640
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

12:04.020 --> 12:09.360
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

12:12.080 --> 12:13.700
And here are your hosts.

12:18.440 --> 12:24.000
This is Bill Vernon and David Cruz. Having looked into Philip Hosey Farmer's feelings on religion

12:24.000 --> 12:30.100
and immortality, we began a look today at the Riverworld series. Farmer explains the basis of the story.

12:30.900 --> 12:37.820
It concerns a planet in which there's a 10 million mile long river which follows the valley.

12:38.600 --> 12:47.500
And everybody has lived from about 150,000 D.C. to about 1883 A.D. was resurrected along

12:47.500 --> 12:56.060
the Bangsley River and rejuvenated for them, looks like they were 25. And the main mystery behind

12:56.060 --> 13:05.880
the whole thing was why were all these people resurrected? Who did it and how?

13:06.920 --> 13:11.860
But the Riverworld concept is so big that Farmer has managed only to scratch the surface in the

13:11.860 --> 13:19.180
four main novels of the series. There are so many themes that I wanted to explore during the course

13:19.180 --> 13:25.440
of those four novels, but I couldn't do it because I would have slowed the story down too much.

13:26.500 --> 13:32.260
It wasn't taking too many sidetracks, you might say, and I'd still be working on that particular

13:32.260 --> 13:37.980
series. What else is left? Listen to Farmer as he gives us an inkling of what he would like to cover.

13:39.080 --> 13:45.620
I didn't go into any detail in how you work out viable societies with people from every place

13:46.190 --> 13:57.560
every time. I also wanted to bring up in depth what would happen to famous people on that planet.

13:58.800 --> 14:05.560
Well, there's Carl Marx, for instance. What would he think of what happened to his

14:06.290 --> 14:13.260
ideas about communism on the planet Earth after he died? Leonardo da Vinci,

14:13.880 --> 14:21.080
his ideas about art, what's the fact that he's on a planet where there are very few pigments

14:21.080 --> 14:25.180
available, for instance, for him to paint? What would he do there?

14:28.220 --> 14:29.470
I also wanted to

14:32.280 --> 14:37.660
bring up various figures from science and the military and philosophy and so forth,

14:38.480 --> 14:42.640
show what they would do there. Now, one of the things about the river world was that

14:44.480 --> 14:50.980
although you were resurrected there in a useful body of your own, as it was in 25 or earlier,

14:51.180 --> 14:59.660
you died before 25. If, for instance, you were 83 when you died and when your mind is still 83,

14:59.660 --> 15:08.780
you have 83 years of experience on Earth behind you. Now, is your character formed? Are you going

15:08.780 --> 15:15.780
to go through perhaps a thousand years being the same person or are you going to improve?

15:16.380 --> 15:19.480
And is the magic labyrinth the last word on the river world?

15:20.300 --> 15:27.460
I made a lot of people mad at me because of that last sentence or your paragraph.

15:27.460 --> 15:31.680
I wrote in the magic labyrinth, everything seems to have been settled,

15:33.700 --> 15:41.620
everything has been cleared up, and then one of the characters, the town of Latterman,

15:42.300 --> 15:49.380
Peter J. Striggett, he's celebrating with the others in the misty tar when he thinks he hears

15:49.380 --> 15:55.480
a football outside in the hallway, blows out, comes back, and says to the others,

15:56.100 --> 16:00.340
I didn't see anyone, it must have been my imagination. A lot of readers got mad at me

16:00.340 --> 16:04.720
because they thought, oh no, he's going right another one. He's leaving a loophole. Well,

16:04.780 --> 16:11.080
I am leaving a loophole. I don't know whether I'll go through it or not, but it's quite possible that

16:11.080 --> 16:18.640
the magic labyrinth wasn't the final one in that series before that everything that

16:19.760 --> 16:23.960
our protagonist learned and everybody else learned is

16:25.080 --> 16:30.760
clearly on through or half-streamed. So the river world novels may or may not be finished,

16:31.160 --> 16:35.380
but we do have some more side stream stories to anticipate, more on Farmer tomorrow.

