This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

23:53.180 --> 23:54.840
And here are your hosts.

23:59.560 --> 24:04.960
This is Bill Vernon and David Cruz. This show will conclude our interview with Philip Jose

24:04.960 --> 24:09.080
Farmer. Yesterday we discussed Farmer's pension for writing under pseudonyms,

24:09.440 --> 24:12.440
as it turns out this practice has a very desirable side effect.

24:13.560 --> 24:20.040
One of the funny things about this is that I found out that I could use the fictional

24:20.040 --> 24:26.300
author device to break a writing block. I had a writing block once, that terrible thing that

24:26.300 --> 24:32.840
sometimes happens to writers, or they don't know what caused this for some reason.

24:33.300 --> 24:37.500
They might have many ideas, be eager to go, but when they sit down in front of the typewriter

24:37.500 --> 24:45.000
nothing happens. Well, that happened to me once. I never thought it would, I thought I was immune

24:45.000 --> 24:52.340
to such a thing. But it did, and after wrestling for two months and getting no place, I had an idea.

24:54.080 --> 24:56.820
I sat down with the typewriter and wrote a story,

24:58.540 --> 25:05.560
not by Philip Jose Farmer, but by David Copperfield, I'd say. I don't remember which

25:05.560 --> 25:14.740
particular nom, the story might be. The story poured out, very good, I thought so anyway.

25:16.200 --> 25:21.920
When I'd completed that, the writing block was gone. See, I wasn't writing then as me,

25:22.920 --> 25:29.920
Philip Jose Farmer, but as I say, Gilbert Trout. And I was in his shoes, I had no trouble. Now,

25:30.020 --> 25:37.500
the funny thing about this is that it's a psychological trick that I'm conscious of,

25:40.220 --> 25:47.860
and yet it works. It's not like I'm trying to trick my unconscious, but I must be doing it one way or

25:48.420 --> 25:55.520
another. Well, I don't know if anybody else has ever broken this writer's block in that manner,

25:55.760 --> 26:02.460
but I recommend trying it. Farmer has also written several books featuring Tarzan or Tarzan-like

26:02.460 --> 26:08.900
characters. Tarzan Alive is Tarzan's biography. The erotic novel A Feast Unknown and its clean

26:08.900 --> 26:14.340
sequels The Mad Goblin and Lord of the Trees feature thinly veiled versions of Tarzan and

26:14.340 --> 26:20.620
Doc Savage. Lord Tiger, the Opar books, and the adventures of the peerless peer also have Tarzan

26:20.620 --> 26:24.880
like protagonists. We asked Farmer when he developed his interest in Tarzan.

26:49.800 --> 26:54.420
But later Farmer picked up on Tarzan again. This time he saw Tarzan in a different light.

27:14.340 --> 27:21.900
This is a very interesting thing before. He was not just a child who'd been cast away

27:21.900 --> 27:27.800
and raised by great apes and then become a creature of the jungle, then returned to playing

27:27.800 --> 27:38.160
sports, and he was sort of an archetype of many, many heroes from classical myth.

27:39.320 --> 27:42.680
And now I'm sure that when Burroughs wrote this, he didn't know what he was doing,

27:42.680 --> 27:47.340
but he did unconsciously. I think it was the creation of Tarzan and the Strogan

27:47.340 --> 27:53.240
Genius. Burroughs is not a great writer, but he has created a great character just like

27:53.780 --> 28:00.060
A. Conan Doyle is not a great writer, but he created a great character, Sherlock Holmes.

28:01.100 --> 28:06.840
Philip Jose Farmer, an author with a seemingly endless supply of unique ideas who appears just

28:06.840 --> 28:08.960
now to be gaining widespread acceptance.

